INSERT INTO `sample_sentences` VALUES (1,'你好。','你好。','This means “Hello” in Chinese. While this literally means “You good,” this is not the way to ask how one is doing, so it is not “Are you good?” or “How are you?” This is also not the way to say “You are good.” The Chinese terms for those will be explained in the next lesson.','This means “Hello” in Chinese. While this literally means “You good,” this is not the way to ask how one is doing, so it is not “Are you good?” or “How are you?” This is also not the way to say “You are good.” The Chinese terms for those will be explained in the next lesson.',1),(2,'A: 你好。\nB: 好。','A: 你好。\nB: 好。','To respond to 你好, you must say 好. There is no need to include the 你 unless you’re the one initiating the greeting.','To respond to 你好, you must say 好. There is no need to include the 你 unless you’re the one initiating the greeting.',1),(3,'你叫什么名字？','你叫什麼名字？','This literally means “What is the name you are called by?” 叫 means “to be called”. 什么 means “what”, which turns the statement into a question. 名字 means “name”.','This literally means “What is the name you are called by?” 叫 means “to be called”. 什麼 means “what”, which turns the statement into a question. 名字 means “name”.',1),(4,'我叫 Aaron。','我叫 Aaron。','When you introduce yourself in English, you say “I am _______.” If your name is Aaron, you say “I am Aaron.” 我 means “I” in Chinese. 叫 means “to be called”, so this literally means “I am called Aaron.” There is another character used more often as a linking verb, but that will be discussed in another lesson. ','When you introduce yourself in English, you say “I am _______.” If your name is Aaron, you say “I am Aaron.” 我 means “I” in Chinese. 叫 means “to be called”, so this literally means “I am called Aaron.” There is another character used more often as a linking verb, but that will be discussed in another lesson. ',1),(5,'我叫王明。','我叫王明。','Chinese names are formally written with the last name first then the first name. In the sentence, the person introduces himself as “王明”. 王 (Wang) is the surname and 明 (Ming) is the first name. In Western languages, romanised Chinese names can be written in the Western order (e.g. Ming Wang) to be consistent with other names, but the order of the Chinese name must be maintained when it is written in Chinese. Note that character names are bolded in the worksheets to avoid confusion.','Chinese names are formally written with the last name first then the first name. In the sentence, the person introduces himself as “王明”. 王 (Wang) is the surname and 明 (Ming) is the first name. In Western languages, romanised Chinese names can be written in the Western order (e.g. Ming Wang) to be consistent with other names, but the order of the Chinese name must be maintained when it is written in Chinese. Note that character names are bolded in the worksheets to avoid confusion.',1),(6,'我叫王明，叫我明。','我叫王明，叫我明。','This means “I am Wang Ming, call me Ming.” This showcases the two ways one can use 叫, as a way to introduce oneself and as “to call”. Note that in Chinese culture, people usually call each other by their full names unless they are close (or in an informal setting), in which they drop the surname. However, it is possible that some people prefer to be called by the first name regardless of how close they are to others.','This means “I am Wang Ming, call me Ming.” This showcases the two ways one can use 叫, as a way to introduce oneself and as “to call”. Note that in Chinese culture, people usually call each other by their full names unless they are close (or in an informal setting), in which they drop the surname. However, it is possible that some people prefer to be called by the first name regardless of how close they are to others.',1),(7,'A: 你叫什么名字？\nB: 我叫王明，你呢？','A: 你叫什麼名字？\nB: 我叫王明，你呢？','你呢 means “And you?” or “How about you?”. 呢 also allows answerers to return the question back to the asker. ','你呢 means “And you?” or “How about you?”. 呢 also allows answerers to return the question back to the asker. ',1),(8,'他叫王明。她叫 Jane。','他叫王明。她叫 Jane。','他 means “he” and 她 is “she”, and while they sound the same when read, they are written differently. Note the key differences between the two characters. ','他 means “he” and 她 is “she”, and while they sound the same when read, they are written differently. Note the key differences between the two characters. ',1),(9,'我认识王明。','我認識王明。','认识 means “to know someone” or “to recognise someone”. Note that this should be used when talking about knowing a certain person. ','認識 means “to know someone” or “to recognise someone”. Note that this should be used when talking about knowing a certain person. ',1),(10,'认识你很高兴，再见！','認識你很高興，再見！','The first part of the sentence literally means “Meeting you is very exciting”, or in simpler terms, “Nice to meet you.” 高兴 means “happy” or “exciting”. 再见 means “Goodbye”, and while it does not directly translate to goodbye, it is a common way of saying it in Chinese. 再见 actually means “See again”, or more completely, “See you again.” ','The first part of the sentence literally means “Meeting you is very exciting”, or in simpler terms, “Nice to meet you.” 高兴 means “happy” or “exciting”. 再见 means “Goodbye”, and while it does not directly translate to goodbye, it is a common way of saying it in Chinese. 再见 actually means “See again”, or more completely, “See you again.” ',1),(11,'很高兴认识你！','很高興認識你！','This is an alternate way of saying “Nice to meet you.” ','This is an alternate way of saying “Nice to meet you.” ',1),(12,'你好吗？','你好嗎？','This means “How are you?” It’s made up of “Hello” (你好) and the question particle 吗, which turns a statement into a yes-or-no question. So it\'s like asking, “Are you well?” or “Are you good?” ','This means “How are you?” It’s made up of “Hello” (你好) and the question particle 吗, which turns a statement into a yes-or-no question. So it\'s like asking, “Are you well?” or “Are you good?” ',2),(13,'A: 你好吗？\nB: 我很好，你呢？','A: 你好嗎？\nB: 我很好，你呢？','One way of replying to “How are you?” is “I am fine” or “I am good”. “我很好” just means that. 很 links the adjective 好 to “I”. ','One way of replying to “How are you?” is “I am fine” or “I am good”. “我很好” just means that. 很 links the adjective 好 to “I”. ',2),(14,'A: 早上好。\nB: 早！','A: 早上好。\nB: 早！','早上好 means “Good morning”. 早 is also another way of greeting someone in the morning, it is the equivalent of saying “Morning!” to someone.','早上好 means “Good morning”. 早 is also another way of greeting someone in the morning, it is the equivalent of saying “Morning!” to someone.',2),(15,'A: 早！你好吗？\nB: 我很好，谢谢。','A: 早！你好嗎？\nB: 我很好，謝謝。','Note that 早 here can be used to start a conversation, unlike 好, which can only be used in response to 你好 or other similar greetings. 谢谢 means “Thank you.” ','Note that 早 here can be used to start a conversation, unlike 好, which can only be used in response to 你好 or other similar greetings. 謝謝 means “Thank you.” ',2),(16,'A: 晚上好，你好吗？\nB: 我很好，谢谢你。\nA: 不客气。','A: 晚上好，你好嗎？\nB: 我很好，謝謝你。\nA: 不客氣。','晚上好 means “Good evening”. Also, to respond to 谢谢, you must say “不客气”. This means “You’re welcome,” “No problem” or “Don’t mention it.” ','晚上好 means “Good evening”. Also, to respond to 謝謝, you must say “不客氣”. This means “You’re welcome,” “No problem” or “Don’t mention it.” ',2),(17,'A: 你认识李华玲吗？\nB: 对不起，我不认识她。','A: 你認識李華玲吗？\nB: 對不起，我不認識她。','Here is another example of a question with 吗. Person A is asking if B knows Li Hualing (李华玲), to which A responds with “Sorry” (对不起) and telling B they do not know her. Note the 不 after 认识, and when put together, means “don’t recognise”, therefore A does not recognise Li Hualing.','Here is another example of a question with 吗. Person A is asking if B knows Li Hualing (李華玲), to which A responds with “Sorry” (對不起) and telling B they do not know her. Note the 不 after 認識, and when put together, means “don’t recognise”, therefore A does not recognise Li Hualing.',2),(18,'A: 对不起。\nB: 没关系。','A: 對不起。\nB: 沒關係。','To respond to “对不起” (I’m sorry), you must say “没关系”, not to be confused with “不客气”, which is used in response to “Thank you.” ','To respond to “ 對不起” (I’m sorry), you must say “沒關係”, not to be confused with “不客氣”, which is used in response to “Thank you.” ',2),(19,'A: 你姓什么？\nB: 我姓张。你姓李吗？\nA: 不，我姓王。','A: 你姓什麼？\nB: 我姓張。你姓李嗎？\nA: 不，我姓王。','“你姓什么？” means “What is your surname?” To answer this question, you must say “我姓___.” In this situation, 姓 is used like a verb that means “to have a surname of”, so Person B tells A that their surname is Zhang (张). Then, they ask A if their surname is Li (李), but A negates this by saying “不” and telling B that their surname is Wang (王).','“你姓什麼？” means “What is your surname?” To answer this question, you must say “我姓___.” In this situation, 姓 is used like a verb that means “to have a surname of”, so Person B tells A that their surname is Zhang (張). Then, they ask A if their surname is Li (李), but A negates this by saying “不” and telling B that their surname is Wang (王).',2),(20,'A: 你姓王吗？\nB: 对，我姓王。你姓张吗？\nA: 不对，我姓李。','A: 你姓王嗎？\nB: 對，我姓王。你姓張嗎？\nA: 不對，我姓李。','Here’s a similar dialogue about asking surnames. Person A asks B if their surname is Wang, to which B says “Correct” (对). B asks A if their surname is Zhang, but A says “That’s not right” (不对) and tells B that their surname is Li.','Here’s a similar dialogue about asking surnames. Person A asks B if their surname is Wang, to which B says “Correct” (對). B asks A if their surname is Zhang, but A says “That’s not right” (不對) and tells B that their surname is Li.',2);
